pian qualities and investigating what these towns can tell us about contemporary modernization and urban planning. She presents the new town movement as something truly global, defying a Cold War East-West dichotomy or the north-south polarization of rich and poor countries. Wherever these new towns were located, whatever their size, whether famous or forgotten, they shared a utopian lineage and conception that, in each case, reveals how residents and planners imagined their ideal urban future.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aCity planningxHistoryy20th century. 0aNew townsxHistoryy20th century. 0aNew townsxPhilosophy. 0aRegional planningxHistoryy20th century. 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh  autopian, intellectual, intellect, intelligence, new town, movement, social studies, history, historical, academic, scholarly, towns, urban, natural resource, river, ocean, water, harbor, proximity, geography, geographical, location, locale, development, colonies, 20th century, contemporary, modern, phenomenon, global, international, tapiola, finland, islamabad, pakistan, cery pontoise, france, modernization.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2016z97831107109840 cprintz978022634603840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226346175423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226346175/original  a978-3-11-071098-4  University of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2016b2016  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles